uclearorange.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nuclearorange</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/20/02 7:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Fusion Orion.</span><hr size=1> I don't know if this can be made workable. It seems credible by the laws of physics but I'm not a physicist. The engineering sounds challenging but it could be possible with some experimentation.<br>
<br>
One of these days I'm really going to buy a graphics package so its easier to illustrate my conceptual ideas. I'll keep this short.<br>
<br>
Basic concept.<br>
<br>
Pulse units are made with no trigger. Fusion bombs minus the fission detonator. No Plutonium or enriched Uranium. Very clean.<br>
<br>
Each pulse unit is detonated by the one fired before it. How close this has to be I dont know. <br>
<br>
I am assuming this premise. Two thermonuclear bombs are touching, with a wall (pusher plate) at one end.<br>
<br>
&lt;BOMB&gt; &lt;BOMB&gt; &lt;PLATE&gt;<br>
<br>
..then one detonates..<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;BOOM!&lt;&lt;&lt; &lt;BOMB&gt; &lt;PLATE&gt;<br>
<br>
..the unit in the middle is caught between a rock and a hard place. Compressed between a wall of thick metal and a fusion detonation it is detonated. A second fusion blast.<br>
<br>
This is where the challenge comes from. To keep this chain reaction going requires pulse units to be fired off within close enough proximity to one another to keep detonating the next in line. <br>
<br>
<br>
&lt;ATOMIC BOMB MACHINE GUN&gt;<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; O &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; O &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; O &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
