&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; O &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; O &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; O &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
<br>
The chain reaction will probably be too fast for the gun. Therefore the devices should be made detonate slowly or purposely built difficult to detonate. Thereby slowing the chain reaction. An atomic blast lasts only a millionth of a second. We would need small pulse units fired off at an incredible rate.<br>
<br>
How close the devices have to be to one another I dont know. That might take testing to discern. The barrel can be protected with vents going off to the sides to disperse the upward blast.<br>
<br>
What do you think? <br>
<br>
The first pulse might have to be a regular thermonuclear bomb. Either that or ground detonated by lasers or possibly minute amounts of anti-matter (if possible).<br>
<br>
