<br>
How do you propose to get that kind of reaction from such a blast?  How could you implode the fusion mass from all directions and make it go critical, just by having explosions near it/  I'm not saying it's impossible <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Just very difficult,wanted to see your ideas on it....and others' ideas.<br>
<br>
Also...what's the energy transfer mechanism from the blast to the spaceship to actually propel it?<br>
<br>
While I don't agree with Orion-type propulsion...it at leats makes logical sense, in terms of heavy elements slamming into the plating at very high speeds to propel the ship.  Fusion devices would release radiation, but very few fission products that are high mass and could add momentum to the craft.  Obviously there is a huge energy from the fusion reaction itself,but how to harvest it? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2119<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/26/02 10:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Fusion Orion.</span><hr size=1> Fusion should be even better than fission at triggering fusion. Ten times the power. Incase you didn't guess, I'm nuclearorange. A take on clockwork orange.<br>
<br>
I was thinking that if we used a concave plate as opposed to the traditional Orion design which is quite the opposite, then the force would be reflected from all sides towards the next pulse device. Similar to encasing a fusion device with a fission trigger.<br>
<br>
<br>
The engineering challenge is to release the bomblets at a rate sufficient keep up with the domino effect we hope to create. Some energy will be lost up the machine gun apperture but vents veering off at slight angles should dissipate this potentially destructive energy. The barrel could run the length of the ship and be constructed of thick metal. <br>
<br>
The shape of the reaction mass would be important. I'm thinking maybe a donut shape. Situated at the top. Thereby creating a circular wall of plasma around the next pulse device which avoids the gun barrel entirely. We don't want the pulse device flying back up the barrel. Yet we do want another pulse device arriving fast on the heels of it. <br>
<br>
Therefore, we might need more than a single barrel. Having multiple guns means faster delivery(our most essential requirement) and each detonation would be at an angle to the next device arriving. Ensuring the energy is not directed up a barrel. Uneven distribution of detonations I know. We can probably get away with it though. Using small pulse devices and a very big ship. The rapidity of detonations would make up for the size anyhow. <br>
<br>
Small rapid blasts would mean a more steady acceleration. Less like what you would expect from fission bomblets.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 9/26/02 10:37:54 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 128<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/28/02 2:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Fusion Orion.</span><hr size=1> 1)how are you setting off the initial reaction?<br>
